"&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nWritten evidence submitted by Alan Morton [FBB0023]&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n2.1.\n&#xa0; \nA publicly funded broadcaster should provide a unique offering and not compete with commercial providers.  \n2.2.\n&#xa0; \nPublic funding should not provide an excuse or opportunity for ‘empire building’.\n2.3.\n&#xa0; \nOverall the BBC’s outp\nut is no better or worse tha\nn\n that of commercial providers.\n2.4.\n&#xa0; \nA publicly funded body should not leave itself open to allegations of political bias.\n2.5.\n&#xa0; \nThe purposes of the BBC as currently defined are too vague and wide ranging. \n2.6.\n&#xa0; \nThe purpose\n of public service br\noadcasting should be narrowly focussed\n.\n \n2.7.\n&#xa0; \nAny operations funded by the public should satisfy the criteria of efficiency, effectiveness and economy.  \n2.8.\n&#xa0; \nThe scope, scale and remit of a publicly funded broadcaster should \nbe \nthe minimum necessary to meet its purpose.  \n2.9.\n&#xa0; \nOutput and services should be determined on the basis of demand and demand should be measured by the willingness of viewers to pay for the service.  \n2.10.\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nProgrammes should be sought from those best able to provide h\nigh quality and good value for money. \n2.11.\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nInnovation should be left to the private sector.  The BBC\n (if it is publicly funded)\n should focus on high quality \nprogramming\n.\n2.12.\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nThe licence fee (BBC Tax) is the most regressive and unfair form of taxation in the UK.  \n2.13.\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nThe compulsory BBC Tax should be abolished and the funding for the BBC should come through subscriptions for its services and / or advertising.\n2.14.\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nThe requirement to provide ‘public service’ broadcasts should be a condition of the broadcast licence applied to\n all broadcasters in the UK.\n2.15.\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nThe basis on which free advertising for their products is given to celebrities by BBC executives should be examined by the National Audit Office. \n2.16.\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nThe current method of governance of the BBC, involving the BBC Trust and Ofcom h\nas failed.  \n2.17.\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nThe lack of accountability and failure of governance would be overcome by adopting the funding mechanism outlined in paragraph 1\n6\n.  \n&#xa0;\nWhat should the BBC be for and what should be the purpose of public service broadcasting?\nHow well has the BBC performed in the curr\nent Charter period in achieving its mission and \npublic purposes?\n&#xa0;\nAre the public purposes in the current Charter the right ones? How might they change?\nWhat scope, scale and remit should the BBC have? \nShould the BBC’s output and services be provided to\n any greater or lesser degree for particular audiences?\nWhat balance should be struck in what th\ne BBC produces in-house, commissions externally and leaves entirely to others to create?\nWhat role should the BBC play in developing technology and new ways of distributing content?\nHow should the BBC be funded beyond 2016?\nHo\nw should the BBC be governed, regulated and held accountable beyond 2016?\n19.1.\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nThe Blue Peter debacle of \n2006\n \nhighlig\nhted\n a culture of duplicity \nwithin\n the BBC.  The all pervasive nature of this culture was acknowledged by the then Direct\nor General when he put in place, at licence payers expense, \na staff training course\n to ameliorate the problem\n.\n19.2.\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nThe Russell Brand / Jona\nthan Ross saga in \n200\n8, together with the Saville \naffair\n suggests \na \ndegree of moral turpitude\n within the management of the BBC.\n19.3.\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nThe connivance between BBC management and its highly paid staff in tax avoidance activities (what the BB\nC\n Trust likes to refer to as the ‘\nfreelancer arrangements’)\n.\n19.4.\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nThe \nseverance\n pay arrangements whereby members of the senior ‘clique’ received payments outside the terms of their contracts amo\nunting to in excess of £25m of Licence P\nayers’ money.\n  (\nIt appears \nthat no one involved in this profligacy has suffered any sa\nn\nction\ns\n. Indeed their arrogant performances at the PAC Hearings suggest no contrition, but then why should they feel any remorse, it was only Licence \nP\nayers money and it went to a good cause – thei\nr friends\n)\n.\n19.5.\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nThe contractual arrangements for \nGeorge Entwistle\n and the severance payment of £450,000\n which he received.\n19.6.\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nThe BBC’s defamation of \nLord McAlpine.\nSummaryThe broadcasting market has changed signifi\ncantly since the BBC was first established\n.\n \n With the wide range of providers now in the broadcast market a new model is required for the provision of ‘public service’ broadcasting and funding of the BBC.  The current system of a compulsory tax on all UK households to fund the BBC is both regressive\n and detrimental to the good management of the organization.  The BBC tax should be abolished and the BBC funded through subscription and / or advertising.  Such a system will resolve many of the governance failures evident in the current arrangements.\n&#xa0;December 2013\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n"